<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="274" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[113,1089,1273,1554]" pageId="1" pageNumber="274">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,230,1273,1297]" pageId="1" pageNumber="274">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species can be distinguished by the dark reddish brown integument of the head and mesosoma (
<figureCitation box="[377,478,1305,1329]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[151,190,1506,1525]" captionTargetBox="[160,1117,217,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[159,1117,216,1484]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs.1–2. Photomicrographs of holotype male of Chiasmognathus saheliensis sp. nov. from Niger:1 – facial aspect; 2 – dorsal aspect." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5325609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5325609/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="274">Figs. 1–2</figureCitation>
); brown metasoma; sparsely punctured mesoscutum, with punctures gradually becoming more dense posteriorly; strongly punctured pleura, with punctures sparse around the episternal scrobe; and the structure of the terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[934,1038,1369,1393]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="3.[114,153,894,913]" captionTargetBox="[140,1059,221,866]" captionTargetId="figure-265@3.[137,1064,217,868]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs. 3–5. Male terminalia of Chiasmognathus saheliensis sp. nov. from Niger: 3 – sternum VII; 4 – sternum VIII; 5 – ventral aspect of genital capsule. Scale bars = 100 μm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5364568" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5364568/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="274">Figs. 3–5</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="277" pageId="1" pageNumber="274" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[113,1089,1273,1554]" lastBlockId="3.[115,1097,992,1592]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="276" pageId="1" pageNumber="274">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,252,1401,1425]" pageId="1" pageNumber="274">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Total body length ca. 
<quantity box="[561,643,1401,1425]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="1" pageNumber="274" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
(estimated by combining lengths of head and mesosoma with that of preserved portions of metasoma which was partial, detached, and previously dissected); forewing length 
<quantity box="[520,603,1465,1489]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="1" pageNumber="274" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
. Head wider than long (width 
<quantity box="[918,1014,1465,1489]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.7" pageId="1" pageNumber="274" unit="mm" value="0.77">0.77 mm</quantity>
, length 
<quantity box="[113,214,1497,1521]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.3" pageId="1" pageNumber="274" unit="mm" value="0.63">0.63 mm</quantity>
); inner margins of compound eyes straight, convergent below; apex of clypeus at lower tangent of compound eyes; ocelli well above upper tangent of compound eyes; clypeus nearly flat; malar space vestigial; mandibles simple, crossing in repose but not covering labrum. Intertegular distance (as measured from between inner margins of tegulae) 
<quantity box="[988,1093,1024,1048]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="276" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.50 mm</quantity>
. Forewing marginal cell broadly truncate; both m-cu crossveins entering second submarginal cell; hind wing with five hamuli. Male terminalia depicted in figures 3–5.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5325609" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5325609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5325609/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="275" startId="2.[151,190,1506,1525]" targetBox="[160,1117,217,1484]" targetPageId="2">
